column11: This question will be resolved using the Mack Institute's analysis for 2017, which will replicate an approach published in a 2015 Nature Climate Change study. In 2016, using a similar method, the Mack Institute found that the average price had declined to $282 per kWh (Mack Institute). Lowering the cost of battery packs through R&D investments, manufacturing improvements, and economies of scale is a major consideration for bringing down the price of battery-powered electric vehicles (BEVs) and making them more competitive with gasoline-fueled internal combustion engines (Bloomberg, The Guardian). Maybe I was too enthusiastic in my first answer and definitely didn't do enough research. I am now going to assume that the rate of change remains constant and guess a 16% decline this year but also acknowledge that with Tesla ramping up mass production prices may fall faster.

Scaling factors are accelerating in 2017 for BEV. Near term (like within 2017), I'd guess that cost decline will still follow the scatter plot from Wharton. Long term, however, it is unclear how much more cost one can squeeze out. Lithium is very mature tech and chemistry doesn't follow Moore's Law. Furthermore, 60%-70% of the world's Cobalt is sourced from Congo, which is an unstable regime. Worse, concentrated sources are prone to cartel-like manipulation.

There is plenty of Lithium available on Earth and large scale investment is continuing in Australia and other countries. According to Wharton Business School, the cost of Lithium-Ion kilowatt hours has decreased at an average rate of 16% per year from 2007-2016. The line-of-best fit on the Wharton scatter plot shows a linear decrease with few outlying data points. According to Wharton, the current cost per kilowatt hour for Lithium-Ion battery packs is $282 and a 16% decrease would leave us at $237. Even if a new and disruptive technology arrived, most large scale factories have set-up and already know what and how they are producing all of next year.
Continuing the 16% a year decline should put it in the 2330 to 245 range, but heavy demand from Tesla and GM and hybrids may start to have an effect anddrive prices lower into the 215 to 230 range.

Looking at https://mackinstitute.wharton.upenn.edu/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/Copy-of-FINAL-BEV-Data.xlsx the results really depend on 1. Will BMW cost drop a lot from 485. 2. Will additional data points appear. If BMW cost does not drop much (stays above 400) and we do not get additional data points, then BMW contributes >$100 to the average cost. Even if other three points goes to $150, the average is $212. If BMW drops to $300 and others don't drop, the cost is $210. If BMW cost does not drop, but 2 more data points appear at around 190 range, the average cost is still at ~239. So really this question is whether BMW costs drop a lot or not.

The Mack chart shows a cluster of 3 lower prices and 1 significantly higher price for 2016, commercial logic would suggest that the outlier (BMW) would disappear in 2017 which would result in a lower average price even if no lower priced suppliers appeared. (Although BMW suggest its new lower cost batteries will not arrive until 2018) There is 230GWh of new battery capacity coming on line. Prices of under $140 KWh are now being quoted. With a lot of new supply, demand may slip behind supply in 2017.

Going by the methodology of the survey, there will likely be only an additional 4-5 data points in the year 2017. With just a handful of these fresh data points, it is unlikely that there will be a huge shift away from the established trend line, which extrapolates the 2017 figure to be about $237. Also, given the action heating up in the battery space, incremental change in the trend is likely to show further acceleration in the dropping of battery costs.
